<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900910-0013</DOCNO><DOCID>900910-0013.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Claims Daimler Unit Sold   Arms to Iraq Spurs Probe   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>09/10/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><CO>   G.DAI EUROP MDEST G.MES</CO><IN>MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><LP>   FRANKFURT -- West German authorities are investigating oneof the aerospace subsidiaries of Daimler-Benz AG for allegedviolations of export-control laws in the delivery of militaryhardware to Iraq.   The public prosecutor's office in Munich said it has begunthe investigation of aircraft makerMesserschmitt-Boelkow-Blohm G.m.b.H., or MBB, amajority-owned subsidiary of Daimler, West Germany's largestindustrial group.</LP><TEXT>   Heinz Stocker, senior district attorney in Munich, saidthe inquiry follows allegations last week by a Germanhuman-rights group, the Society for Endangered People, thatit uncovered what it called military hardware for Iraq at anMBB storage site in Hoehenkirchen.   MBB denied the allegations that it planned to shipmilitary hardware to Iraq. It said it halted sales to Iraq inaccordance with the United Nations embargo, of which WestGermany is a participant. The company said it has beenselling helicopters to Iraq since 1978, but that thosemachines haven't been outfitted for military applications.The company also supplies replacement parts for thehelicopters, but MBB said Friday that it ceased suchdeliveries to Iraq Aug. 6.   MBB said the parcels at the depot are being held therebecause of the Iraqi trade embargo.</TEXT></DOC>